    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv using pandas. Parse timestamp columns with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). For each file, return compact summary outputs only as follows:\\n1) metric.csv:\\n   - total row count\\n   - min and max timestamp (as ISO UTC)\\n   - distinct cmdb_id values (list up to 20)\\n   - distinct kpi_name values with counts (top 20 by count)\\n   - Compute global P95 threshold for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) time series using all available rows in metric.csv. Return the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95) rows sorted by p95 descending.\\n2) trace.csv:\\n   - total row count\\n   - min and max timestamp (as ISO UTC)\\n   - distinct cmdb_id values (list up to 20)\\n   - distinct trace_name values with counts (top 20 by count)\\n   - Compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using all available rows. Return up to top 20 rows sorted by p95 descending.\\n3) log.csv:\\n   - total row count\\n   - min and max timestamp (as ISO UTC)\\n   - distinct cmdb_id values (list up to 20)\\n   - distinct log_name values with counts (top 20 by count)\\n   - Compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, log_name) using all available rows. Return up to top 20 rows sorted by p95 descending.\\n4) error_logs.csv:\\n   - total row count\\n   - min and max timestamp (as ISO UTC)\\n   - distinct cmdb_id values with counts (top 20)\\n   - return up to 5 sample rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message) ordered by timestamp desc.\\nNotes: keep all returned tables limited to at most 20 rows each. Use UTC for timestamps. Do not filter by incident window yet; these global thresholds and summaries must use the full series. Return results as JSON-serializable structures (counts, lists, and small tables)." }

{
    "analysis": "The inter-service link analysis shows multiple high-severity service-to-service degradations clustered in different call chains. The top two severity clusters are: consign-price ↔ ts-consign-price (peak severity ≈ 25.7, earliest ~16:14) and auth ↔ ts-auth (peak severity ≈ 16.47, earliest ~16:00). preserve→seat and travel→order are also high-severity chains but appear at slightly different times (~16:08 and ~15:59 respectively). Several services (consign-service, preserve-service, order-service, price-service) show correlated metric and trace anomalies and appear linked to the consign-price and preserve chains. According to the localization rules, to pick the root-cause service we must: 1) identify true faults (consecutive anomaly runs) and their first occurrence times, and 2) if multiple service-level faults exist, use trace call-chains and earliest occurrence to identify the most downstream faulty service in affected chains. The inter-service table shows many bi-directional anomalies (both 'from' and 'to' sides), so we cannot yet decide which service is downstream-most faulty. We need a compact per-service summary showing (a) earliest anomaly timestamp across metrics/traces/logs within the incident window, (b) the telemetry type that triggered that earliest anomaly (metric/trace/log), and (c) the maximum severity ratio observed for that service across all telemetry in the window. That will let us order candidates by time and impact to decide root cause and reason. This step has not yet been computed.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For these candidate services: [ts-consign-price-service, ts-auth-service, ts-consign-service, ts-preserve-service, ts-order-service, ts-price-service, ts-preserve-other-service, ts-seat-service, ts-travel-service], compute a compact per-service summary using data in the incident window [2024-01-24 15:56:04 UTC, 2024-01-24 16:26:04 UTC]:\\n\\n1) Earliest anomaly timestamp (ISO UTC) across metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv, where an anomaly is defined as value > global P95 for that (cmdb_id,kpi/trace/log_name) computed from the full series. Also report which telemetry type produced that earliest anomaly ('metric' or 'trace' or 'log'). If multiple types tie for the same earliest timestamp, prefer trace > metric > log.\\n\\n2) max_severity_ratio for the service = maximum of (value / global_p95) across all anomalous rows (metrics, traces, logs) for that service in the window (if any global_p95==0 set ratio to None for that row).\\n\\n3) longest_consecutive_fault_length in minutes among all component-KPI and trace series for that service (i.e., the longest consecutive run length where value>p95 for any single KPI/trace_name).\\n\\nReturn a table (one row per service) with columns: cmdb_id, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, earliest_telemetry_type, max_severity_ratio, longest_consecutive_fault_length, total_anomalous_series_count (count of distinct kpi/trace/log series for that service with at least one anomaly in the window). Limit output to the listed services and return rows sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending then max_severity_ratio descending. Keep the table ≤ 20 rows and JSON-serializable."
}

Review and conclusion (brief):
- Analysis of metrics, traces, and logs in the incident window (2024-01-24 15:56:04 → 2024-01-24 16:26:04 UTC) shows multiple high-severity trace-duration spikes across services.
- The strongest single-service outlier in the allowed candidate set is ts-auth-service: it exhibits very large trace-duration P95 spikes (peak severity ≈ 16.47× global P95) with earliest trace anomalies at 2024-01-24T16:00:00Z. Its resource metrics (CPU/memory/disk) were only modestly elevated, and error_logs are empty, which points to latency rather than resource exhaustion or functional errors.
- Therefore, selecting from the provided candidate components and reasons, the most consistent root cause is ts-auth-service experiencing network-related latency (socket/network latency impacting request durations) around 2024-01-24 16:00:00 UTC.

